# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: analytic-number-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In mathematics, **analytic number theory** is a branch of number theory that uses methods from mathematical analysis to solve problems about the integers.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] It is often said to have begun with Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet's 1837 introduction of Dirichlet *L*-functions to give the first proof of Dirichlet's theorem on arithmetic progressions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] It is well known for its results on prime numbers (involving the Prime Number Theorem and Riemann zeta function) and additive number theory (such as the Goldbach conjecture and Waring's problem).
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Analytic number theory can be split up into two major parts, divided more by the type of problems they attempt to solve than fundamental differences in technique.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Much of analytic number theory was inspired by the prime number theorem.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Let π(*x*) be the prime-counting function that gives the number of primes less than or equal to *x*, for any real number *x*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] For example, π(10) = 4 because there are four prime numbers (2, 3, 5 and 7) less than or equal to 10.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] known as the asymptotic law of distribution of prime numbers.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Adrien-Marie Legendre conjectured in 1797 or 1798 that π(*a*) is approximated by the function *a*/(*A* ln(*a*) + *B*), where *A* and *B* are unspecified constants.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In the second edition of his book on number theory (1808) he then made a more precise conjecture, with *A* = 1 and *B* ≈ −1.08366.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] But Gauss never published this conjecture.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In 1838 Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet came up with his own approximating function, the logarithmic integral li(*x*) (under the slightly different form of a series, which he communicated to Gauss).
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Both Legendre's and Dirichlet's formulas imply the same conjectured asymptotic equivalence of π(*x*) and *x* / ln(*x*) stated above, although it turned out that Dirichlet's approximation is considerably better if one considers the differences instead of quotients.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Johann Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet is credited with the creation of analytic number theory, a field in which he found several deep results and in proving them introduced some fundamental tools, many of which were later named after him.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In 1837 he published Dirichlet's theorem on arithmetic progressions, using mathematical analysis concepts to tackle an algebraic problem and thus creating the branch of analytic number theory.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In proving the theorem, he introduced the Dirichlet characters and L-functions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In 1841 he generalized his arithmetic progressions theorem from integers to the ring of Gaussian integers $\mathbb {Z} [i]$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In two papers from 1848 and 1850, the Russian mathematician Pafnuty L'vovich Chebyshev attempted to prove the asymptotic law of distribution of prime numbers.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] He was able to prove unconditionally that this ratio is bounded above and below by two explicitly given constants near to 1 for all *x*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Although Chebyshev's paper did not prove the Prime Number Theorem, his estimates for π(*x*) were strong enough for him to prove Bertrand's postulate that there exists a prime number between *n* and 2*n* for any integer *n* ≥ 2.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Riemann's statement of the Riemann hypothesis, from his 1859 paper.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] (He was discussing a version of the zeta function, modified so that its roots are real rather than on the critical line.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Bernhard Riemann made some famous contributions to modern analytic number theory.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In a single short paper (the only one he published on the subject of number theory), he investigated the Riemann zeta function and established its importance for understanding the distribution of prime numbers.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] He made a series of conjectures about properties of the zeta function, one of which is the well-known Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Extending the ideas of Riemann, two proofs of the prime number theorem were obtained independently by Jacques Hadamard and Charles Jean de la Vallée-Poussin and appeared in the same year (1896).
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Both proofs used methods from complex analysis, establishing as a main step of the proof that the Riemann zeta function ζ(*s*) is non-zero for all complex values of the variable *s* that have the form *s* = 1 + *it* with *t* > 0.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] The biggest technical change after 1950 has been the development of *sieve methods*, particularly in multiplicative problems.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] These are combinatorial in nature, and quite varied.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] The extremal branch of combinatorial theory has in return been greatly influenced by the value placed in analytic number theory on quantitative upper and lower bounds.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Another recent development is *probabilistic number theory*, which uses methods from probability theory to estimate the distribution of number theoretic functions, such as how many prime divisors a number has.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Developments within analytic number theory are often refinements of earlier techniques, which reduce the error terms and widen their applicability.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] For example, the *circle method* of Hardy and Littlewood was conceived as applying to power series near the unit circle in the complex plane; it is now thought of in terms of finite exponential sums (that is, on the unit circle, but with the power series truncated).
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] The needs of Diophantine approximation are for auxiliary functions that are not generating functions—their coefficients are constructed by use of a pigeonhole principle—and involve several complex variables.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] The fields of Diophantine approximation and transcendence theory have expanded, to the point that the techniques have been applied to the Mordell conjecture.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Theorems and results within analytic number theory tend not to be exact structural results about the integers, for which algebraic and geometrical tools are more appropriate.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Instead, they give approximate bounds and estimates for various number theoretical functions, as the following examples illustrate.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Euclid showed that there are infinitely many prime numbers.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] An important question is to determine the asymptotic distribution of the prime numbers; that is, a rough description of how many primes are smaller than a given number.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In 1859 Bernhard Riemann used complex analysis and a special meromorphic function now known as the Riemann zeta function to derive an analytic expression for the number of primes less than or equal to a real number *x*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Remarkably, the main term in Riemann's formula was exactly the above integral, lending substantial weight to Gauss's conjecture.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Riemann found that the error terms in this expression, and hence the manner in which the primes are distributed, are closely related to the complex zeros of the zeta function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Using Riemann's ideas and by getting more information on the zeros of the zeta function, Jacques Hadamard and Charles Jean de la Vallée-Poussin managed to complete the proof of Gauss's conjecture.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] This remarkable result is what is now known as the *prime number theorem*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] It is a central result in analytic number theory.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Loosely speaking, it states that given a large number *N*, the number of primes less than or equal to *N* is about *N*/log(*N*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] More generally, the same question can be asked about the number of primes in any arithmetic progression *a* + *nq* for any integer *n*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In one of the first applications of analytic techniques to number theory, Dirichlet proved that any arithmetic progression with *a* and *q* coprime contains infinitely many primes.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] There are also many deep and wide-ranging conjectures in number theory whose proofs seem too difficult for current techniques, such as the twin prime conjecture which asks whether there are infinitely many primes *p* such that *p* + 2 is prime.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] On the assumption of the Elliott–Halberstam conjecture it has been proven recently that there are infinitely many primes *p* such that *p* + *k* is prime for some positive even *k* at most 12.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Also, it has been proven unconditionally (i.e. not depending on unproven conjectures) that there are infinitely many primes *p* such that *p* + *k* is prime for some positive even *k* at most 246.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] The case for squares, *k* = 2, was answered by Lagrange in 1770, who proved that every positive integer is the sum of at most four squares.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] The general case was proved by Hilbert in 1909, using algebraic techniques which gave no explicit bounds.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] An important breakthrough was the application of analytic tools to the problem by Hardy and Littlewood.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Diophantine problems are concerned with integer solutions to polynomial equations: one may study the distribution of solutions, that is, counting solutions according to some measure of "size" or *height*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In geometrical terms, given a circle centered about the origin in the plane with radius *r*, the problem asks how many integer lattice points lie on or inside the circle.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] It is not hard to prove that the answer is $\pi r^{2}+E(r)$ , where $E(r)/r^{2}\to 0$ as $r\to \infty$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Again, the difficult part and a great achievement of analytic number theory is obtaining specific upper bounds on the error term *E*(*r*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] It was shown by Gauss that $E(r)=O(r)$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In general, an *O*(*r*) error term would be possible with the unit circle (or, more properly, the closed unit disk) replaced by the dilates of any bounded planar region with piecewise smooth boundary.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Furthermore, replacing the unit circle by the unit square, the error term for the general problem can be as large as a linear function of *r*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Therefore, getting an error bound of the form $O(r^{\delta })$ for some $\delta <1$ in the case of the circle is a significant improvement.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] The first to attain this was Sierpiński in 1906, who showed $E(r)=O(r^{2/3})$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In 1915, Hardy and Landau each showed that one does *not* have $E(r)=O(r^{1/2})$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Since then the goal has been to show that for each fixed $\epsilon >0$ there exists a real number $C(\epsilon )$ such that $E(r)\leq C(\epsilon )r^{1/2+\epsilon }$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In 2000 Huxley showed that $E(r)=O(r^{131/208})$ , which is the best published result.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Depending on the choice of coefficients $a_{n}$ , this series may converge everywhere, nowhere, or on some half plane.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In many cases, even where the series does not converge everywhere, the holomorphic function it defines may be analytically continued to a meromorphic function on the entire complex plane.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] hence the coefficients of the product of two Dirichlet series are the multiplicative convolutions of the original coefficients.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Furthermore, techniques such as partial summation and Tauberian theorems can be used to get information about the coefficients from analytic information about the Dirichlet series.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] where the product is taken over all prime numbers *p*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Euler's proof of the infinity of prime numbers makes use of the divergence of the term at the left hand side for *s* = 1 (the so-called harmonic series), a purely analytic result.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Euler was also the first to use analytical arguments for the purpose of studying properties of integers, specifically by constructing generating power series.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] This was the beginning of analytic number theory.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Later, Riemann considered this function for complex values of *s* and showed that this function can be extended to a meromorphic function on the entire plane with a simple pole at *s* = 1.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] This function is now known as the Riemann Zeta function and is denoted by *ζ*(*s*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] There is a plethora of literature on this function and the function is a special case of the more general Dirichlet L-functions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Analytic number theorists are often interested in the error of approximations such as the prime number theorem.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In this case, the error is smaller than *x*/log *x*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Riemann's formula for π(*x*) shows that the error term in this approximation can be expressed in terms of the zeros of the zeta function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] In his 1859 paper, Riemann conjectured that all the "non-trivial" zeros of ζ lie on the line $\Re (s)=1/2$ but never provided a proof of this statement.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] This famous and long-standing conjecture is known as the *Riemann Hypothesis* and has many deep implications in number theory; in fact, many important theorems have been proved under the assumption that the hypothesis is true.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] For example, under the assumption of the Riemann Hypothesis, the error term in the prime number theorem is $O(x^{1/2+\varepsilon })$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] Hardy and Littlewood proved many results about the zeta function in an attempt to prove the Riemann Hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/analytic-number-theory] This led to several theorems describing the density of the zeros on the critical line.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] In number theory, an **arithmetic**, **arithmetical**, or **number-theoretic function** is generally any function whose domain is the set of positive integers and whose range is a subset of the complex numbers.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Hardy & Wright include in their definition the requirement that an arithmetical function "expresses some arithmetical property of *n*".
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] There is a larger class of number-theoretic functions that do not fit this definition, for example, the prime-counting functions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] This article provides links to functions of both classes.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] An example of an arithmetic function is the divisor function whose value at a positive integer *n* is equal to the number of divisors of *n*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Arithmetic functions are often extremely irregular (see table), but some of them have series expansions in terms of Ramanujan's sum.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Two whole numbers *m* and *n* are called coprime if their greatest common divisor is 1, that is, if there is no prime number that divides both of them.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] The notations ${\textstyle \sum _{d\mid n}f(d)}$ and ${\textstyle \prod _{d\mid n}f(d)}$ mean that the sum or product is over all positive divisors of *n*, including 1 and *n*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] The notations can be combined: ${\textstyle \sum _{p\mid n}f(p)}$ and ${\textstyle \prod _{p\mid n}f(p)}$ mean that the sum or product is over all prime divisors of *n*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] For example, if *n* = 18, then $\sum _{p\mid 18}f(p)=f(2)+f(3),$ and similarly ${\textstyle \sum _{p^{k}\mid n}f(p^{k})}$ and ${\textstyle \prod _{p^{k}\mid n}f(p^{k})}$ mean that the sum or product is over all prime powers dividing *n*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] The fundamental theorem of arithmetic states that any positive integer *n* can be represented uniquely as a product of powers of primes: $n=p_{1}^{a_{1}}\cdots p_{k}^{a_{k}}$ where *p*1 < *p*2 < ... < *p**k* are primes and the *aj* are positive integers.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] It is often convenient to write this as an infinite product over all the primes, where all but a finite number have a zero exponent.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Define the *p*-adic valuation **ν*p*(*n*)** to be the exponent of the highest power of the prime *p* that divides *n*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] That is, if *p* is one of the *p**i* then *ν**p*(*n*) = *a**i*, otherwise it is zero.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] To avoid repetition, formulas for the functions listed in this article are, whenever possible, given in terms of *n* and the corresponding *p**i*, *a**i*, *ω*, and Ω.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Since a positive number to the zero power is one, ***σ*0(*n*)** is therefore the number of (positive) divisors of *n*; it is usually denoted by ***d*(*n*)** or ***τ*(*n*)** (for the German *Teiler* = divisors).
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Even though it is defined as a sum of complex numbers (irrational for most values of *q*), it is an integer.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] All **Dirichlet characters *χ*(*n*)** are completely multiplicative.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] For a fixed prime *p*, ***ν**p*(*n*)**, defined above as the exponent of the largest power of *p* dividing *n*, is completely additive.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] These important functions (which are not arithmetic functions) are defined for non-negative real arguments, and are used in the various statements and proofs of the prime number theorem.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] They are summation functions (see the main section just below) of arithmetic functions which are neither multiplicative nor additive.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] A related function counts prime powers with weight 1 for primes, 1/2 for their squares, 1/3 for cubes, etc.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] The second Chebyshev function *ψ*(*x*) is the summation function of the von Mangoldt function just below.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Given an arithmetic function *a*(*n*), its **summation function** *A*(*x*) is defined by $A(x):=\sum _{n\leq x}a(n).$ *A* can be regarded as a function of a real variable.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Given a positive integer *m*, *A* is constant along open intervals *m* < *x* < *m* + 1, and has a jump discontinuity at each integer for which *a*(*m*) ≠ 0.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Individual values of arithmetic functions may fluctuate wildly – as in most of the above examples.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Summation functions "smooth out" these fluctuations.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] In some cases it may be possible to find asymptotic behaviour for the summation function for large *x*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] An **average order of an arithmetic function** is some simpler or better-understood function which has the same summation function asymptotically, and hence takes the same values "on average".
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] The example above shows that *d*(*n*) has the average order log(*n*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Given an arithmetic function *a*(*n*), let *F**a*(*s*), for complex *s*, be the function defined by the corresponding Dirichlet series (where it converges): $F_{a}(s):=\sum _{n=1}^{\infty }{\frac {a(n)}{n^{s}}}.$ *F**a*(*s*) is called a generating function of *a*(*n*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] The simplest such series, corresponding to the constant function *a*(*n*) = 1 for all *n*, is *ζ*(*s*) the Riemann zeta function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Consider two arithmetic functions *a* and *b* and their respective generating functions *F**a*(*s*) and *F**b*(*s*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] This function *c* is called the Dirichlet convolution of *a* and *b*, and is denoted by $a*b$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] If *f* is multiplicative, then so is *g*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] If *f* is completely multiplicative, then *g* is multiplicative, but may or may not be completely multiplicative.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] There are a great many formulas connecting arithmetical functions with each other and with the functions of analysis, especially powers, roots, and the exponential and log functions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] The page divisor sum identities contains many more generalized and related examples of identities involving arithmetic functions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] That is, if *n* is odd, *σ**k**(*n*) is the sum of the *k*th powers of the divisors of *n*, that is, *σ**k*(*n*), and if *n* is even it is the sum of the *k*th powers of the even divisors of *n* minus the sum of the *k*th powers of the odd divisors of *n*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] The sequence $c_{n}=\sum _{i=0}^{n}a_{i}b_{n-i}$ is called the convolution or the Cauchy product of the sequences *a**n* and *b**n*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] These formulas may be proved analytically (see Eisenstein series) or by elementary methods.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Since *σ**k*(*n*) (for natural number *k*) and *τ*(*n*) are integers, the above formulas can be used to prove congruences for the functions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] See Ramanujan tau function for some examples.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Extend the domain of the partition function by setting *p*(0) = 1.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet discovered formulas that relate the class number *h* of quadratic number fields to the Jacobi symbol.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] An integer *D* is called a **fundamental discriminant** if it is the discriminant of a quadratic number field.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] This is equivalent to *D* ≠ 1 and either a) *D* is squarefree and *D* ≡ 1 (mod 4) or b) *D* ≡ 0 (mod 4), *D*/4 is squarefree, and *D*/4 ≡ 2 or 3 (mod 4).
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] There is also a formula relating *r*3 and *h*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Again, let *D* be a fundamental discriminant, *D* < −4.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] The Riemann hypothesis is also equivalent to the statement that, for all *n* > 5040, $\sigma (n)<e^{\gamma }n\log \log n$ (where γ is the Euler–Mascheroni constant).
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] This has been generalized by a number of mathematicians.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] In fact, if *f* is any arithmetical function $\sum _{\stackrel {1\leq k\leq n}{\gcd(k,n)=1}}f(\gcd(k-1,n))=\varphi (n)\sum _{d\mid n}{\frac {(\mu *f)(d)}{\varphi (d)}},$ where * stands for Dirichlet convolution.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Let *m* and *n* be distinct, odd, and positive.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Let *D*(*n*) be the arithmetic derivative.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] Then the logarithmic derivative ${\frac {D(n)}{n}}=\sum _{\stackrel {p\mid n}{p{\text{ prime}}}}{\frac {v_{p}(n)}{p}}.$ See *Arithmetic derivative* for details.
[src:analytic-number-theory/arithmetic-function] See Multiplicative group of integers modulo n and Primitive root modulo n.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] In number theory, **Dirichlet's theorem**, also called the **Dirichlet prime number theorem**, states that for any two positive coprime integers *a* and *d*, there are infinitely many primes of the form *a* + *nd*, where *n* is also a positive integer.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] In other words, there are infinitely many primes that are congruent to *a* modulo *d*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] and Dirichlet's theorem states that this sequence contains infinitely many prime numbers.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] The theorem extends Euclid's theorem that there are infinitely many prime numbers (of the form 1 + 2*n*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Stronger forms of Dirichlet's theorem state that for any such arithmetic progression, the sum of the reciprocals of the prime numbers in the progression diverges and that different such arithmetic progressions with the same modulus have approximately the same proportions of primes.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Equivalently, the primes are evenly distributed (asymptotically) among the congruence classes modulo *d* containing *a* coprime to *d*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] The theorem is named after the German mathematician Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet, who proved it in 1837.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Sequences *dn* + *a* with odd *d* are often ignored because half the numbers are even and the other half is the same numbers as a sequence with 2*d*, if we start with *n* = 0.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] For example, 6*n* + 1 produces the same primes as 3*n* + 1, while 6*n* + 5 produces the same as 3*n* + 2 except for the only even prime 2.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] The following table lists several arithmetic progressions with infinitely many primes and the first few ones in each of them.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] We can generate some forms of primes by using an iterative method.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] We then continue this process to find successive primes of the form 4*n* + 3 (Silverman 2013).
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Since the primes thin out, on average, in accordance with the prime number theorem, the same must be true for the primes in arithmetic progressions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] It is natural to ask about the way the primes are shared between the various arithmetic progressions for a given value of *d* (there are *d* of those, essentially, if we do not distinguish two progressions sharing almost all their terms).
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] contains a proportion 1/(*q* − 1) of the primes.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] When compared to each other, progressions with a quadratic nonresidue remainder have typically slightly more elements than those with a quadratic residue remainder (Chebyshev's bias).
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] In 1737, Euler related the study of prime numbers to what is known now as the Riemann zeta function: he showed that the value *ζ*(1) reduces to a ratio of two infinite products, Π *p* / Π (*p* − 1), for all primes *p*, and that the ratio is infinite.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] In 1775, Euler stated the theorem for the cases of *a* + *nd*, where *a* = 1.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] This special case of Dirichlet's theorem can be proven using cyclotomic polynomials.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] The general form of the theorem was first conjectured by Legendre in his attempted unsuccessful proofs of quadratic reciprocity — as Gauss noted in his *Disquisitiones Arithmeticae* — but it was proved by Dirichlet (1837) with Dirichlet *L*-series.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] The proof is modeled on Euler's earlier work relating the Riemann zeta function to the distribution of primes.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] The theorem represents the beginning of rigorous analytic number theory.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Atle Selberg gave an elementary proof of this theorem in 1949.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Dirichlet's theorem is proved by showing that the value of the Dirichlet L-function (of a non-trivial character) at 1 is nonzero.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] The proof of this statement requires some calculus and analytic number theory (Serre 1973).
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] The particular case *a* = 1 (i.e., concerning the primes that are congruent to 1 modulo some *n*) can be proven by analyzing the splitting behavior of primes in cyclotomic extensions, without making use of calculus (Neukirch 1999, §VII.6).
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Although the proof of Dirichlet's Theorem makes use of calculus and analytic number theory, some proofs of examples are much more straightforward.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] In particular, the proof of the example of infinitely many primes of the form 4*n* + 3 makes an argument similar to the one made in the proof of Euclid's theorem (Silverman 2013).
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] We want to prove that there are infinitely many primes of the form 4*n* + 3.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Assume, for contradiction, that there are only finitely many primes of the form 4*n* + 3.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] It is clear that none of the primes in the list 3, *p*1, *p*2, ..., *p**m* divide *N*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] By cases, *N* is either composite or prime.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] If *N* is composite, then *N* has a unique prime factorization *N* = *a*1*a*2...*a**r*, where each *a**i* is prime.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Because *N* ≡ 3 (mod 4), *N* is odd and must be the product of only odd primes.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Any odd prime *p* must be such that *p* ≡ 1 (mod 4) or *p* ≡ 3 (mod 4).
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] It cannot be that *a**i* ≡ 1 (mod 4) ∀*a**i* because if this were the case, then *N* ≡ 1 (mod 4).
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] So there exists a prime *a*′ ≡ 3 (mod 4) such that *a*′ | *N* and *a*′ < *N*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Otherwise, if *N* is prime, then by definition *N* ≡ 3 (mod 4).
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] So in both cases respectively, *a*′ and *N* satisfy the form 4*n* + 3, but are not in the list 3, *p*1, *p*2, ..., *p**m* since they both divide *N*, which is a contradiction.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Therefore, this list doesn't contain all such primes and there must be infinitely many primes of the form 4*n* + 3 (Silverman 2013).
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] The Bunyakovsky conjecture generalizes Dirichlet's theorem to higher-degree polynomials.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Whether or not even simple quadratic polynomials such as *x*2 + 1 (known from Landau's fourth problem) attain infinitely many prime values is an important open problem.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Dickson's conjecture generalizes Dirichlet's theorem to more than one polynomial.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Schinzel's hypothesis H generalizes these two conjectures, i.e. generalizes to more than one polynomial with degree larger than one.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] In algebraic number theory, Dirichlet's theorem generalizes to the Chebotarev's density theorem.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Linnik's theorem (1944) concerns the size of the smallest prime in a given arithmetic progression.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Linnik proved that the progression *a* + *nd* (as *n* ranges through the positive integers) contains a prime of magnitude at most *cdL* for absolute constants *c* and *L*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Subsequent researchers have reduced *L* to 5.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] An analogue of Dirichlet's theorem holds in the framework of dynamical systems (T.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-theorem-on-arithmetic-progressions] Shiu showed that any arithmetic progression satisfying the hypothesis of Dirichlet's theorem will in fact contain arbitrarily long runs of *consecutive* prime numbers.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-series] In mathematics, a **Dirichlet series** is any series of the form $\sum _{n=1}^{\infty }{\frac {a_{n}}{n^{s}}},$ where *s* is complex, and $a_{n}$ is a complex sequence.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-series] It is a special case of general Dirichlet series.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-series] Dirichlet series play a variety of important roles in analytic number theory.
[src:analytic-number-theory/dirichlet-series] The most usually seen definition of the Riemann zeta function is a Dirichlet series, as are the Dirichlet *L*-functions.
