[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] In mathematics, the **prime-counting function** is the function counting the number of prime numbers less than or equal to some real number x.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] It is denoted by *π*(*x*) (unrelated to the number π).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] A symmetric variant seen sometimes is *π*0(*x*), which is equal to *π*(*x*) − 1⁄2 if x is exactly a prime number, and equal to *π*(*x*) otherwise.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] That is, the number of prime numbers less than x, plus half if x equals a prime.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] Of great interest in number theory is the growth rate of the prime-counting function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] It was conjectured in the end of the 18th century by Gauss and by Legendre to be approximately ${\frac {x}{\log x}}$ where log is the natural logarithm, in the sense that $\lim _{x\rightarrow \infty }{\frac {\pi (x)}{x/\log x}}=1.$ This statement is the prime number theorem.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] An equivalent statement is $\lim _{x\rightarrow \infty }{\frac {\pi (x)}{\operatorname {li} (x)}}=1$ where li is the logarithmic integral function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] The prime number theorem was first proved in 1896 by Jacques Hadamard and by Charles de la Vallée Poussin independently, using properties of the Riemann zeta function introduced by Riemann in 1859.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] Proofs of the prime number theorem not using the zeta function or complex analysis were found around 1948 by Atle Selberg and by Paul Erdős (for the most part independently).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] In 1899, de la Vallée Poussin proved that $\pi (x)=\operatorname {li} (x)+O\left(xe^{-a{\sqrt {\log x}}}\right)\quad {\text{as }}x\to \infty$ for some positive constant a.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] More precise estimates of *π*(*x*) are now known.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] For values of x that are not unreasonably large, li(*x*) is greater than *π*(*x*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] However, *π*(*x*) − li(*x*) is known to change sign infinitely many times.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] For a discussion of this, see Skewes' number.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] The Riemann hypothesis suggests that every such non-trivial zero lies along Re(*s*) = ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] The table shows how the three functions *π*(*x*), ⁠*x*/log *x*⁠, and li(*x*) compared at powers of 10.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] The value for *π*(1024) was originally computed by J.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] Kleinjung assuming the Riemann hypothesis.
