[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] Using his method and an IBM 701, Lehmer was able to compute the correct value of *π*(109) and missed the correct value of *π*(1010) by 1.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] Further improvements to this method were made by Lagarias, Miller, Odlyzko, Deléglise, and Rivat.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] Other prime-counting functions are also used because they are more convenient to work with.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] Riemann's prime-power counting function is usually denoted as Π0(*x*) or *J*0(*x*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-counting-function] It has jumps of ⁠1/*n*⁠ at prime powers pn and it takes a value halfway between the two sides at the discontinuities of *π*(*x*).
