[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] In mathematics, the **prime number theorem** (**PNT**) describes the asymptotic distribution of prime numbers among the positive integers.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] It formalizes the intuitive idea that primes become less common as they become larger by precisely quantifying the rate at which this occurs.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The theorem was proved independently by Jacques Hadamard and Charles Jean de la Vallée Poussin in 1896 using ideas introduced by Bernhard Riemann (in particular, the Riemann zeta function).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The first such distribution found is *π*(*N*) ~ ⁠*N*/log(*N*)⁠, where *π*(*N*) is the prime-counting function (the number of primes less than or equal to *N*) and log(*N*) is the natural logarithm of N.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] This means that for large enough N, the probability that a random integer not greater than N is prime is very close to 1 / log(*N*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] In other words, the average gap between consecutive prime numbers among the first N integers is roughly log(*N*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Consequently, a random integer with at most 2*n* digits (for large enough n) is about half as likely to be prime as a random integer with at most n digits.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] For example, among the positive integers of at most 1000 digits, about one in 2300 is prime (log(101000) ≈ 2302.6), whereas among positive integers of at most 2000 digits, about one in 4600 is prime (log(102000) ≈ 4605.2).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Let *π*(*x*) be the prime-counting function defined to be the number of primes less than or equal to x, for any real number x.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] For example, *π*(10) = 4 because there are four prime numbers (2, 3, 5 and 7) less than or equal to 10.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] known as the **asymptotic law of distribution of prime numbers**.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] This notation (and the theorem) does *not* say anything about the limit of the *difference* of the two functions as x increases without bound.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Instead, the theorem states that *x* / log *x* approximates *π*(*x*) in the sense that the relative error of this approximation approaches 0 as x increases without bound.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] the asymptotic notation meaning, again, that the relative error of this approximation approaches 0 as n increases without bound.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] where $M(x)=\sum _{n\leq x}\mu (n)$ is the Mertens function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Based on the tables by Anton Felkel and Jurij Vega, Adrien-Marie Legendre conjectured in 1797 or 1798 that *π*(*a*) is approximated by the function *a* / (*A* log *a* + *B*) , where A and B are unspecified constants.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] In the second edition of his book on number theory (1808) he then made a more precise conjecture, with *A* = 1 and *B* = −1.08366 .
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Carl Friedrich Gauss considered the same question at age 15 or 16 "in the year 1792 or 1793", according to his own recollection in 1849.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Both Legendre's and Dirichlet's formulas imply the same conjectured asymptotic equivalence of *π*(*x*) and *x* / log(*x*) stated above, although it turned out that Dirichlet's approximation is considerably better if one considers the differences instead of quotients.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] In two papers from 1848 and 1850, the Russian mathematician Pafnuty Chebyshev attempted to prove the asymptotic law of distribution of prime numbers.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] His work is notable for the use of the zeta function *ζ*(*s*), for real values of the argument "s", as in works of Leonhard Euler, as early as 1737.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Chebyshev's papers predated Riemann's celebrated memoir of 1859, and he succeeded in proving a slightly weaker form of the asymptotic law, namely, that if the limit as x goes to infinity of *π*(*x*) / (*x* / log(*x*)) exists at all, then it is necessarily equal to one.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] He was able to prove unconditionally that this ratio is bounded above and below by 0.92129 and 1.10555, for all sufficiently large x.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Although Chebyshev's paper did not prove the Prime Number Theorem, his estimates for *π*(*x*) were strong enough for him to prove Bertrand's postulate that there exists a prime number between *n* and 2*n* for any integer *n* ≥ 2.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] An important paper concerning the distribution of prime numbers was Riemann's 1859 memoir "On the Number of Primes Less Than a Given Magnitude", the only paper he ever wrote on the subject.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Riemann introduced new ideas into the subject, chiefly that the distribution of prime numbers is intimately connected with the zeros of the analytically extended Riemann zeta function of a complex variable.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] In particular, it is in this paper that the idea to apply methods of complex analysis to the study of the real function *π*(*x*) originates.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Extending Riemann's ideas, two proofs of the asymptotic law of the distribution of prime numbers were found independently by Jacques Hadamard and Charles Jean de la Vallée Poussin and appeared in the same year (1896).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Both proofs used methods from complex analysis, establishing as a main step of the proof that the Riemann zeta function *ζ*(*s*) is nonzero for all complex values of the variable s that have the form *s* = 1 + *it* with *t* > 0 .
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] During the 20th century, the theorem of Hadamard and de la Vallée Poussin also became known as the Prime Number Theorem.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Several different proofs of it were found, including the "elementary" proofs of Atle Selberg (1949) and Paul Erdős (1949).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Hadamard's and de la Vallée Poussin's original proofs are long and elaborate; later proofs introduced various simplifications through the use of Tauberian theorems but remained difficult to digest.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] A short proof was discovered in 1980 by the American mathematician Donald J.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Newman's proof is arguably the simplest known proof of the theorem, although it is not "elementary" since it uses Cauchy's integral theorem from complex analysis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Here is a sketch of the proof referred to in one of Terence Tao's lectures.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Like most proofs of the PNT, it starts out by reformulating the problem in terms of a less intuitive, but better-behaved, prime-counting function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The idea is to count the primes (or a related set such as the set of prime powers) with *weights* to arrive at a function with smoother asymptotic behavior.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The next step is to find a useful representation for *ψ*(*x*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Let *ζ*(*s*) be the Riemann zeta function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] holds, where the sum is over all zeros (trivial and nontrivial) of the zeta function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] This striking formula is one of the so-called explicit formulas of number theory, and is already suggestive of the result we wish to prove, since the term x (claimed to be the correct asymptotic order of *ψ*(*x*)) appears on the right-hand side, followed by (presumably) lower-order asymptotic terms.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The next step in the proof involves a study of the zeros of the zeta function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The nontrivial zeros, namely those on the critical strip 0 ≤ Re(*s*) ≤ 1, can potentially be of an asymptotic order comparable to the main term x if Re(*ρ*) = 1, so we need to show that all zeros have real part strictly less than 1.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Certainly y is not zero, since *ζ*(*s*) has a simple pole at *s* = 1.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Suppose that *x* > 1 and let x tend to 1 from above.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Since $\zeta (s)$ has a simple pole at *s* = 1 and *ζ*(*x* + 2*iy*) stays analytic, the left hand side in the previous inequality tends to 0, a contradiction.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Finally, we can conclude that the PNT is heuristically true.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] To rigorously complete the proof there are still serious technicalities to overcome, due to the fact that the summation over zeta zeros in the explicit formula for *ψ*(*x*) does not converge absolutely but only conditionally and in a "principal value" sense.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] There are several ways around this problem but many of them require rather delicate complex-analytic estimates.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Another method is to use Ikehara's Tauberian theorem, though this theorem is itself quite hard to prove.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Newman observed that the full strength of Ikehara's theorem is not needed for the prime number theorem, and one can get away with a special case that is much easier to prove.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Newman gives a quick proof of the prime number theorem (PNT).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The proof is "non-elementary" by virtue of relying on complex analysis, but uses only elementary techniques from a first course in the subject: Cauchy's integral formula, Cauchy's integral theorem and estimates of complex integrals.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] One further piece of information needed in Newman's proof, and which is the key to the estimates in his simple method, is that $\ {\tfrac {\ \vartheta (x)\ }{x}}\$ is bounded.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] This is proved using an ingenious and easy method due to Chebyshev.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] converges, and therefore the integrand goes to zero as $\ t\to \infty \ ,$ which is the PNT.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] In general, the convergence of the improper integral does not imply that the integrand goes to zero at infinity, since it may oscillate, but since $\ \vartheta \$ is increasing, it is easy to show in this case.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Indeed, this integral is strongly suggestive of the notion that the "density" of primes around t should be 1 / log *t*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] So, the prime number theorem can also be written as *π*(*x*) ~ Li(*x*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] for some positive constant a, where *O*(...) is the big O notation.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The connection between the Riemann zeta function and *π*(*x*) is one reason the Riemann hypothesis has considerable importance in number theory: if established, it would yield a far better estimate of the error involved in the prime number theorem than is available today.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] (this last estimate is in fact equivalent to the Riemann hypothesis).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] This latter bound has been shown to express a variance to mean power law (when regarded as a random function over the integers) and ⁠1/ f ⁠ noise and to also correspond to the Tweedie compound Poisson distribution.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] (The Tweedie distributions represent a family of scale invariant distributions that serve as foci of convergence for a generalization of the central limit theorem.) A lower bound is also derived by J.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The logarithmic integral li(*x*) is larger than *π*(*x*) for "small" values of x.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] This is because it is (in some sense) counting not primes, but prime powers, where a power pn of a prime p is counted as ⁠1/ n ⁠ of a prime.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] This suggests that li(*x*) should usually be larger than *π*(*x*) by roughly $\ {\tfrac {1}{2}}\operatorname {li} ({\sqrt {x}})\ ,$ and in particular should always be larger than *π*(*x*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] However, in 1914, Littlewood proved that $\ \pi (x)-\operatorname {li} (x)\$ changes sign infinitely often.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The first value of x where *π*(*x*) exceeds li(*x*) is probably around *x* ~ 10316 ; see the article on Skewes' number for more details.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] In the first half of the twentieth century, some mathematicians (notably G.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Hardy) believed that there exists a hierarchy of proof methods in mathematics depending on what sorts of numbers (integers, reals, complex) a proof requires, and that the prime number theorem (PNT) is a "deep" theorem by virtue of requiring complex analysis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] This belief was somewhat shaken by a proof of the PNT based on Wiener's tauberian theorem, though Wiener's proof ultimately relies on properties of the Riemann zeta function on the line $Re(s)=1$ , where complex analysis must be used.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] By July of that year, Selberg and Paul Erdős had each obtained elementary proofs of the PNT, both using Selberg's asymptotic formula as a starting point.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] These proofs effectively laid to rest the notion that the PNT was "deep" in that sense, and showed that technically "elementary" methods were more powerful than had been believed to be the case.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] On the history of the elementary proofs of the PNT, including the Erdős–Selberg priority dispute, see an article by Dorian Goldfeld.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] There is some debate about the significance of Erdős and Selberg's result.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] There is no rigorous and widely accepted definition of the notion of elementary proof in number theory, so it is not clear exactly in what sense their proof is "elementary".
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Although it does not use complex analysis, it is in fact much more technical than the standard proof of PNT.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] One possible definition of an "elementary" proof is "one that can be carried out in first-order Peano arithmetic." There are number-theoretic statements (for example, the Paris–Harrington theorem) provable using second order but not first-order methods, but such theorems are rare to date.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Erdős and Selberg's proof can certainly be formalized in Peano arithmetic, and in 1994, Charalambos Cornaros and Costas Dimitracopoulos proved that their proof can be formalized in a very weak fragment of PA, namely *I*Δ0 + exp.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] However, this does not address the question of whether or not the standard proof of PNT can be formalized in PA.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] A more recent "elementary" proof of the prime number theorem uses ergodic theory, due to Florian Richter.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The prime number theorem is obtained there in an equivalent form that the Cesàro sum of the values of the Liouville function is zero.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The Liouville function is $(-1)^{\omega (n)}$ where $\omega (n)$ is the number of prime factors, with multiplicity, of the integer n .
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] This ergodic theorem can also be used to give "soft" proofs of results related to the prime number theorem, such as the Pillai–Selberg theorem and Erdős–Delange theorem.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] In 2005, Avigad *et al.* employed the Isabelle theorem prover to devise a computer-verified variant of the Erdős–Selberg proof of the PNT.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] This was the first machine-verified proof of the PNT.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Avigad chose to formalize the Erdős–Selberg proof rather than an analytic one because while Isabelle's library at the time could implement the notions of limit, derivative, and transcendental function, it had almost no theory of integration to speak of.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] In 2009, John Harrison employed HOL Light to formalize a proof employing complex analysis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] By developing the necessary analytic machinery, including the Cauchy integral formula, Harrison was able to formalize "a direct, modern and elegant proof instead of the more involved 'elementary' Erdős–Selberg argument".
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Let *π**d*,*a*(*x*) denote the number of primes in the arithmetic progression *a*, *a* + *d*, *a* + 2*d*, *a* + 3*d*, ... that are less than x.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] In other words, the primes are distributed evenly among the residue classes [*a*] modulo d with gcd(*a*, *d*) = 1 .
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] This is stronger than Dirichlet's theorem on arithmetic progressions (which only states that there is an infinity of primes in each class) and can be proved using similar methods used by Newman for his proof of the prime number theorem.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The Siegel–Walfisz theorem gives a good estimate for the distribution of primes in residue classes.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Bennett *et al.* proved the following estimate that has explicit constants A and B (Theorem 1.3): Let d $\geq 3$ be an integer and let a be an integer that is coprime to d.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] empirically the primes congruent to 3 are more numerous and are nearly always ahead in this "prime number race"; the first reversal occurs at *x* = 26861.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] so the lead in the race switches back and forth infinitely many times.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The phenomenon that *π*4,3(*x*) is ahead most of the time is called Chebyshev's bias.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The prime number race generalizes to other moduli and is the subject of much research; Pál Turán asked whether it is always the case that *π**c*,*a*(*x*) and *π**c*,*b*(*x*) change places when a and b are coprime to c.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Granville and Martin give a thorough exposition and survey.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Another example is the distribution of the last digit of prime numbers.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Except for 2 and 5, all prime numbers end in 1, 3, 7, or 9.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Dirichlet's theorem states that asymptotically, 25% of all primes end in each of these four digits.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] However, empirical evidence shows that, for a given limit, there tend to be slightly more primes that end in 3 or 7 than end in 1 or 9 (a generation of the Chebyshev's bias).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] This follows that 1 and 9 are quadratic residues modulo 10, and 3 and 7 are quadratic nonresidues modulo 10.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The prime number theorem is an *asymptotic* result.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The first inequality holds for all *x* ≥ 599 and the second one for *x* ≥ 355991.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] In Pierre Dusart's thesis there are stronger versions of this type of inequality that are valid for larger x.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Note that the first of these obsoletes the *ε* > 0 condition on the lower bound.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Again considering the 2×1017th prime number 8512677386048191063, assuming the trailing error term is zero gives an estimate of 8512681315554715386; the first 5 digits match and relative error is about 0.46 parts per million.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] where each *Pi* is a degree-i monic polynomial.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Dusart (1999). found tighter bounds using the form of the Cesàro/Cipolla approximations but varying the lowest-order constant term.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The upper bounds can be extended to smaller n by loosening the parameter.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Again, the bound on n may be decreased by loosening the parameter.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The table compares exact values of *π*(*x*) to the two approximations *x* / log *x* and li(*x*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The approximation difference columns are rounded to the nearest integer, but the "% error" columns are computed based on the unrounded approximations.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The last column, *x* / *π*(*x*), is the average prime gap below x.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The value for *π*(1024) was originally computed assuming the Riemann hypothesis; it has since been verified unconditionally.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] There is an analogue of the prime number theorem that describes the "distribution" of irreducible polynomials over a finite field; the form it takes is strikingly similar to the case of the classical prime number theorem.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] To state it precisely, let *F* = GF(*q*) be the finite field with q elements, for some fixed q, and let Nn be the number of monic *irreducible* polynomials over F whose degree is equal to n.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] That is, we are looking at polynomials with coefficients chosen from F, which cannot be written as products of polynomials of smaller degree.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] In this setting, these polynomials play the role of the prime numbers, since all other monic polynomials are built up of products of them.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] Since there are precisely *q**n* monic polynomials of degree n (including the reducible ones), this can be rephrased as follows: if a monic polynomial of degree n is selected randomly, then the probability of it being irreducible is about ⁠1/*n*⁠.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The proofs of these statements are far simpler than in the classical case.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] where the sum is over all divisors d of n.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] (This formula was known to Gauss.) The main term occurs for *d* = *n*, and it is not difficult to bound the remaining terms.
[src:analytic-number-theory/prime-number-theorem] The "Riemann hypothesis" statement depends on the fact that the largest proper divisor of n can be no larger than ⁠*n*/2⁠.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Do all non-trivial zeros of the Riemann zeta function have a real part equal to one half?
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] In mathematics, the **Riemann hypothesis** is the conjecture that the Riemann zeta function has its zeros only at the negative even integers and complex numbers with real part ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Many consider it to be the most important unsolved problem in pure mathematics.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] It is of great interest in number theory because it implies results about the distribution of prime numbers.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] It was proposed by Bernhard Riemann, after whom it is named.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] According to a 2026 survey, there is overwhelming numerical evidence for the hypothesis, but no proof is known.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The name is also used for some closely related analogues, some of which have been proved, such as the Riemann hypothesis for curves over finite fields, which was proved by André Weil.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The Riemann zeta function $\zeta$ is a function whose argument may be any complex number other than 1, and whose values are also complex.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] It has zeros at the negative even integers; that is, $\zeta (s)=0$ when s is one of $-2,-4,-6,\dots$ These are called its *trivial zeros*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The zeta function is also zero for other values of s , which are called *nontrivial zeros*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Thus, the hypothesis states that all the nontrivial zeros lie on the *critical line*, consisting of the complex numbers ${\tfrac {1}{2}}+it$ where t is a real number and i is the imaginary unit.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Leonhard Euler considered this series in the 1730s for real values of s , in conjunction with his solution to the Basel problem.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] where the infinite product extends over all prime numbers p .
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The Riemann hypothesis discusses zeros outside the region of convergence of this series and Euler product.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] To make sense of the hypothesis, it is necessary to analytically continue the function to obtain a form that is valid for all complex s .
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Because the zeta function is meromorphic, all choices of how to perform this analytic continuation will lead to the same result, by the identity theorem.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] within the region of convergence for both series.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] But the eta function series on the right converges not just when the real part of s is greater than one, but more generally whenever s has positive real part.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Thus, the zeta function can be redefined as $\eta (s)/(1-2/2^{s})$ , extending it from $\operatorname {Re} (s)>1$ to the larger domain $\operatorname {Re} (s)>0$ , except for the points where $1-2/2^{s}$ is zero.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] These are the points $s=1+2\pi in/\log 2$ , where n can be any nonzero integer; the zeta function can be extended to these values too by taking limits (see the article on the Dirichlet eta function), giving a finite value for all values of s with positive real part except the simple pole at $s=1$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] One may then define $\zeta (s)$ for all remaining nonzero complex numbers s ( $\operatorname {Re} (s)\leq 0$ and $s\neq 0$ ) by applying this equation outside the strip, and letting $\zeta (s)$ equal the right side of the equation whenever s has non-positive real part (and $s\neq 0$ ).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] If s is a negative even integer, then $\zeta (s)=0$ , because the factor $\sin(\pi s/2)$ vanishes; these are the zeta function's *trivial zeros*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The value *ζ*(0) = −1/2 is not determined by the functional equation, but is the limiting value of $\zeta (s)$ as s approaches zero.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The functional equation also implies that the zeta function has no zeros with negative real part other than the trivial zeros, so all nontrivial zeros lie in the *critical strip* where s has real part between 0 and 1.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] — Riemann's statement of the Riemann hypothesis, from (Riemann 1859).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] — Jacques Hadamard, The Mathematician's Mind, VIII.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Riemann's original motivation for studying the zeta function and its zeros was their occurrence in his explicit formula for the number of primes $\pi (x)$ less than or equal to a given number x , which he published in his 1859 paper "On the Number of Primes Less Than a Given Magnitude".
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] which counts the primes and prime powers up to x , counting a prime power $p^{n}$ as $1/n$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The summation in Riemann's formula is not absolutely convergent, but may be evaluated by taking the zeros $\rho$ in order of the absolute value of their imaginary part.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The other terms also correspond to zeros: the dominant term $\operatorname {li} (x)$ comes from the pole at $s=1$ , considered as a zero of multiplicity $-1$ , and the remaining small terms come from the trivial zeros.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] For some graphs of the sums of the first few terms of this series see Riesel & Göhl (1970) or Zagier (1977).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] This formula says that the zeros of the Riemann zeta function control the oscillations of primes around their "expected" positions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Riemann knew that the non-trivial zeros of the zeta function were symmetrically distributed about the line $s=1/2+it$ , and he knew that all of its non-trivial zeros must lie in the range $0\leq \operatorname {Re} (s)\leq 1$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] He checked that a few of the zeros lay on the critical line with real part $1/2$ and suggested that they all do; this is the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The practical uses of the Riemann hypothesis include many propositions known to be true under the Riemann hypothesis, and some that can be shown to be equivalent to the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Riemann's explicit formula for the number of primes less than a given number states that, in terms of a sum over the zeros of the Riemann zeta function, the magnitude of the oscillations of primes around their expected position is controlled by the real parts of the zeros of the zeta function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] In particular, the error term in the prime number theorem is closely related to the position of the zeros.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] For example, if $\beta$ is the upper bound of the real parts of the zeros, then $\pi (x)-\operatorname {li} (x)=O\!\left(x^{\beta }\log x\right)$ , where $\pi (x)$ is the prime-counting function and $\operatorname {li} (x)$ is the logarithmic integral function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] It is already known that $1/2\leq \beta \leq 1$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Helge von Koch proved that the Riemann hypothesis implies the "best possible" bound for the error of the prime number theorem.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] for all $x\geq 73.2$ , where $\psi (x)$ is Chebyshev's second function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The constant $4/\pi$ may be reduced to $1+\varepsilon$ provided that x is taken to be sufficiently large.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] This is an explicit version of a theorem of Cramér.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The Riemann hypothesis implies strong bounds on the growth of many other arithmetic functions, in addition to the primes counting function above.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] One example involves the Möbius function *μ*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] is valid for every *s* with real part greater than 1/2, with the sum on the right hand side converging, is equivalent to the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] for every positive *ε* is equivalent to the Riemann hypothesis (J.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Littlewood, 1912; see for instance: paragraph 14.25 in Titchmarsh (1986)).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The determinant of the order *n* Redheffer matrix is equal to *M*(*n*), so the Riemann hypothesis can also be stated as a condition on the growth of these determinants.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Littlewood's result has been improved several times since then, by Edmund Landau, Edward Charles Titchmarsh, Helmut Maier and Hugh Montgomery, and Kannan Soundararajan.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The Riemann hypothesis is equivalent to many other conjectures about the rate of growth of other arithmetic functions aside from *μ*(*n*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] for all *n* > 5040 if and only if the Riemann hypothesis is true, where *γ* is the Euler–Mascheroni constant.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] for every natural number *n* > 1, where $H_{n}$ is the *n*th harmonic number.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] is true for all *n* ≥ 120569#, where *φ*(*n*) is Euler's totient function and 120569# is the product of the first 120569 primes.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Another example was found by Jérôme Franel, and extended by Landau (see Franel & Landau (1924)).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The Riemann hypothesis is equivalent to several statements showing that the terms of the Farey sequence are fairly regular.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] is equivalent to the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] is the number of terms in the Farey sequence of order *n*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The Riemann hypothesis also implies quite sharp bounds for the growth rate of the zeta function in other regions of the critical strip.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] so the growth rate of *ζ*(1 + *it*) and its inverse would be known up to a factor of 2.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The prime number theorem implies that on average, the gap between the prime *p* and its successor is log *p*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] However, some gaps between primes may be much larger than the average.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Cramér proved that, assuming the Riemann hypothesis, every gap is *O*(√*p* log *p*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] This is a case in which even the best bound that can be proved using the Riemann hypothesis is far weaker than what seems true: Cramér's conjecture implies that every gap is *O*((log *p*)2), which, while larger than the average gap, is far smaller than the bound implied by the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Numerical evidence supports Cramér's conjecture.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Many statements equivalent to the Riemann hypothesis have been found, though so far none of them have led to much progress in proving (or disproving) it.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] holds for all ε > 0 if and only if the Riemann hypothesis holds.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] See also the Hardy–Littlewood criterion.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] is dense in the Hilbert space *L*2(0,1) of square-integrable functions on the unit interval.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Beurling (1955) extended this by showing that the zeta function has no zeros with real part greater than 1/*p* if and only if this function space is dense in *Lp*(0,1).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] This Nyman-Beurling criterion was strengthened by Baez-Duarte to the case where $\theta _{\nu }\in \{1/k\}_{k\geq 1}$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] has no non-trivial bounded solutions $\varphi$ for $1/2<\sigma <1$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Weil's criterion is the statement that the positivity of a certain function is equivalent to the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Related is Li's criterion, a statement that the positivity of a certain sequence of numbers is equivalent to the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] That *ζ*(*s*) has only simple zeros on the critical line is equivalent to its derivative having no zeros on the critical line.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The Farey sequence provides two equivalences, due to Jerome Franel and Edmund Landau in 1924.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The de Bruijn–Newman constant denoted by Λ and named after Nicolaas Govert de Bruijn and Charles M.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] has only real zeros if and only if *λ* ≥ Λ.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Since the Riemann hypothesis is equivalent to the claim that all the zeroes of *H*(0, *z*) are real, the Riemann hypothesis is equivalent to the conjecture that Λ ≤ 0.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Brad Rodgers and Terence Tao discovered the equivalence is actually Λ = 0 by proving zero to be the lower bound of the constant.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Proving zero is also the upper bound would therefore prove the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Newman noted that this conjecture (now theorem) "is a quantitative version of the dictum that the Riemann hypothesis, if true, is only barely so." As of April 2020 the upper bound is Λ ≤ 0.2.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Several applications use the generalized Riemann hypothesis for Dirichlet L-series or zeta functions of number fields rather than just the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Many basic properties of the Riemann zeta function can easily be generalized to all Dirichlet L-series, so it is plausible that a method that proves the Riemann hypothesis for the Riemann zeta function would also work for the generalized Riemann hypothesis for Dirichlet L-functions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Several results first proved using the generalized Riemann hypothesis were later given unconditional proofs without using it, though these were usually much harder.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Many of the consequences on the following list are taken from Conrad (2010).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Some consequences of the RH are also consequences of its negation, and are thus theorems.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] In their discussion of the Hecke, Deuring, Mordell, Heilbronn theorem, Ireland & Rosen (1990, p.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Care should be taken to understand what is meant by saying the generalized Riemann hypothesis is false: one should specify exactly which class of Dirichlet series has a counterexample.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] This concerns the sign of the error in the prime number theorem.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] It has been computed that π(*x*) < li(*x*) for all *x* ≤ 1025 (see this table), and no value of *x* is known for which π(*x*) > li(*x*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Thus the difference π(*x*) − li(*x*) changes sign infinitely many times.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Skewes' number is an estimate of the value of *x* corresponding to the first sign change.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Littlewood's proof is divided into two cases: the RH is assumed false (about half a page of Ingham 1932, Chapt.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] V), and the RH is assumed true (about a dozen pages).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Stanisław Knapowski followed this up with a paper on the number of times $\Delta (n)$ changes sign in the interval $\Delta (n)$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] This is the conjecture (first stated in article 303 of Gauss's *Disquisitiones Arithmeticae*) that there are only finitely many imaginary quadratic fields with a given class number.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] One way to prove it would be to show that as the discriminant *D* → −∞ the class number *h*(*D*) → ∞.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The following sequence of theorems involving the Riemann hypothesis is described in Ireland & Rosen 1990, pp.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] In 1935, Carl Siegel strengthened the result without using RH or GRH in any way.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Nicolas proved that $\varphi (n)<e^{-\gamma }{\frac {n}{\log \log n}}$ for infinitely many *n*, where *φ*(*n*) is Euler's totient function and *γ* is Euler's constant.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The Riemann hypothesis can be generalized by replacing the Riemann zeta function by the formally similar, but much more general, global L-functions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] In this broader setting, one expects the non-trivial zeros of the global *L*-functions to have real part 1/2.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] It is these conjectures, rather than the classical Riemann hypothesis only for the single Riemann zeta function, which account for the true importance of the Riemann hypothesis in mathematics.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The most common generalized Riemann hypothesis extends the Riemann hypothesis to all Dirichlet L-functions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] In particular it implies the conjecture that Siegel zeros (zeros of *L*-functions between 1/2 and 1) do not exist.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The extended Riemann hypothesis extends the Riemann hypothesis to all Dedekind zeta functions of algebraic number fields.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Since Dedekind zeta function for abelian extension of the rationals can be expressed as product of Dirichlet L-functions and only possible pole is in 1 for Riemann zeta function (thus no pole can cancel nontrivial zero), this version of Riemann hypothesis implies generalized Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The Riemann hypothesis can also be extended to the *L*-functions of Hecke characters of number fields.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Since Dirichlet L-functions are Hecke L-functions for finite characters, then this hypothesis directly implies generalized Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Dedekind zeta functions can be expressed as product of Hecke L-functions and only possible pole of Hecke L-function is at 1, then this version of Riemann Hypothesis implies also version for Dedekind zeta functions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] There are two approaches for extension of Riemann hypothesis that seem to be the most general.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The grand Riemann hypothesis extends it to all Automorphic L-functions, such as Mellin transforms of Hecke eigenforms.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The Riemann hypothesis for Selberg class extends it rather for functions satisfying some properties (at least conjecturaly satisfied by most functions usually called *zeta functions* or *L-functions*) than for functions defined by direct formula.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Though it is expected that Selberg class should be equal to class of automorphic L-functions, and thus this approaches should be equivalent, this is important open problem itself and part of Langlands program.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Artin (1924) introduced global zeta functions of (quadratic) function fields and conjectured an analogue of the Riemann hypothesis for them, which has been proved by Hasse in the genus 1 case and by Weil (1948) in general.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] For instance, the fact that the Gauss sum, of the quadratic character of a finite field of size *q* (with *q* odd), has absolute value ${\sqrt {q}}$ is actually an instance of the Riemann hypothesis in the function field setting.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] This led Weil (1949) to conjecture a similar statement for all algebraic varieties; the resulting Weil conjectures were proved by Pierre Deligne.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Arithmetic zeta functions generalise the Riemann and Dedekind zeta functions as well as the zeta functions of varieties over finite fields to every arithmetic scheme or a scheme of finite type over integers.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The arithmetic zeta function of a regular connected equidimensional arithmetic scheme of Kronecker dimension *n* can be factorized into the product of appropriately defined L-factors and an auxiliary factor.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Assuming a functional equation and meromorphic continuation, the generalized Riemann hypothesis for the L-factor states that its zeros inside the critical strip $\Re (s)\in (0,n)$ lie on the central line.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] This is known for schemes in positive characteristic and follows from Pierre Deligne, but remains entirely unknown in characteristic zero.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Selberg (1956) introduced the Selberg zeta function of a Riemann surface.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] These are similar to the Riemann zeta function: they have a functional equation, and an infinite product similar to the Euler product but taken over closed geodesics rather than primes.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The Selberg trace formula is the analogue for these functions of the explicit formulas in prime number theory.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Selberg proved that the Selberg zeta functions satisfy the analogue of the Riemann hypothesis, with the imaginary parts of their zeros related to the eigenvalues of the Laplacian operator of the Riemann surface.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The Ihara zeta function of a finite graph is an analogue of the Selberg zeta function, which was first introduced by Yasutaka Ihara in the context of discrete subgroups of the two-by-two p-adic special linear group.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] A regular finite graph is a Ramanujan graph, a mathematical model of efficient communication networks, if and only if its Ihara zeta function satisfies the analogue of the Riemann hypothesis as was pointed out by T.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Montgomery (1973) suggested the pair correlation conjecture that the correlation functions of the (suitably normalized) zeros of the zeta function should be the same as those of the eigenvalues of a random hermitian matrix.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Odlyzko (1987) showed that this is supported by large-scale numerical calculations of these correlation functions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Montgomery showed that (assuming the Riemann hypothesis) at least 2/3 of all zeros are simple, and a related conjecture is that all zeros of the zeta function are simple (or more generally have no non-trivial integer linear relations between their imaginary parts).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Dedekind zeta functions of algebraic number fields, which generalize the Riemann zeta function, often do have multiple complex zeros.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] This is because the Dedekind zeta functions factorize as a product of powers of Artin L-functions, so zeros of Artin L-functions sometimes give rise to multiple zeros of Dedekind zeta functions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Other examples of zeta functions with multiple zeros are the L-functions of some elliptic curves: these can have multiple zeros at the real point of their critical line; the Birch-Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture predicts that the multiplicity of this zero is the rank of the elliptic curve.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] There are many other examples of zeta functions with analogues of the Riemann hypothesis, some of which have been proved.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Goss zeta functions of function fields have a Riemann hypothesis, proved by Sheats (1998).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Several mathematicians have addressed the Riemann hypothesis, but none of their attempts has yet been accepted as a proof.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Watkins (2021) lists some incorrect solutions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Hilbert and Pólya suggested that one way to derive the Riemann hypothesis would be to find a self-adjoint operator, from the existence of which the statement on the real parts of the zeros of *ζ*(*s*) would follow when one applies the criterion on real eigenvalues.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Odlyzko (1987) showed that the distribution of the zeros of the Riemann zeta function shares some statistical properties with the eigenvalues of random matrices drawn from the Gaussian unitary ensemble.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] This gives some support to the Hilbert–Pólya conjecture.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] In 1999, Michael Berry and Jonathan Keating conjectured that there is some unknown quantization ${\hat {H}}$ of the classical Hamiltonian *H* = *xp* so that $\zeta (1/2+i{\hat {H}})=0$ and even more strongly, that the Riemann zeros coincide with the spectrum of the operator $1/2+i{\hat {H}}$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] This is in contrast to canonical quantization, which leads to the Heisenberg uncertainty principle $\sigma _{x}\sigma _{p}\geq {\frac {\hbar }{2}}$ and the natural numbers as spectrum of the quantum harmonic oscillator.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The crucial point is that the Hamiltonian should be a self-adjoint operator so that the quantization would be a realization of the Hilbert–Pólya program.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The analogy with the Riemann hypothesis over finite fields suggests that the Hilbert space containing eigenvectors corresponding to the zeros might be some sort of first cohomology group of the spectrum Spec (*Z*) of the integers.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Deninger (1998) described some of the attempts to find such a cohomology theory.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Cartier (1982) discussed a related example, where due to a bizarre bug a computer program listed zeros of the Riemann zeta function as eigenvalues of the same Laplacian operator.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Schumayer & Hutchinson (2011) surveyed some of the attempts to construct a suitable physical model related to the Riemann zeta function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The Lee–Yang theorem states that the zeros of certain partition functions in statistical mechanics all lie on a "critical line" with their real part equal to 0, and this has led to some speculation about a relationship with the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Pál Turán showed that if the functions $\sum _{n=1}^{N}n^{-s}$ have no zeros when the real part of *s* is greater than one then $T(x)=\sum _{n\leq x}{\frac {\lambda (n)}{n}}\geq 0{\text{ for }}x>0,$ where λ(*n*) is the Liouville function given by (−1)*r* if *n* has *r* prime factors.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] He showed that this in turn would imply that the Riemann hypothesis is true.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] But Haselgrove (1958) proved that *T*(*x*) is negative for infinitely many *x* (and also disproved the closely related Pólya conjecture), and Borwein, Ferguson & Mossinghoff (2008) showed that the smallest such *x* is 72185376951205.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Spira (1968) showed by numerical calculation that the finite Dirichlet series above for *N* = 19 has a zero with real part greater than 1.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Therefore, Turán's result is vacuously true and cannot help prove the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Alain Connes has described a relationship between the Riemann hypothesis and noncommutative geometry, and showed that a suitable analog of the Selberg trace formula for the action of the idèle class group on the adèle class space would imply the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Some of these ideas are elaborated in Lapidus (2008).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Louis de Branges showed that the Riemann hypothesis would follow from a positivity condition on a certain Hilbert space of entire functions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] However Conrey & Li (2000) showed that the necessary positivity conditions are not satisfied.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Despite this obstacle, de Branges has continued to work on an attempted proof of the Riemann hypothesis along the same lines, but this has not been widely accepted by other mathematicians.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] The Riemann hypothesis implies that the zeros of the zeta function form a quasicrystal, a distribution with discrete support whose Fourier transform also has discrete support.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Dyson (2009) suggested trying to prove the Riemann hypothesis by classifying, or at least studying, 1-dimensional quasicrystals.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] In dimension one the study of the zeta integral in Tate's thesis does not lead to new important information on the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Contrary to this, in dimension two work of Ivan Fesenko on two-dimensional generalisation of Tate's thesis includes an integral representation of a zeta integral closely related to the zeta function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] In this new situation, not possible in dimension one, the poles of the zeta function can be studied via the zeta integral and associated adele groups.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Related conjecture of Ivan Fesenko on the positivity of the fourth derivative of a boundary function associated to the zeta integral essentially implies the pole part of the generalized Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Suzuki (2011) proved that the latter, together with some technical assumptions, implies Fesenko's conjecture.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] Deligne's proof of the Riemann hypothesis over finite fields used the zeta functions of product varieties, whose zeros and poles correspond to sums of zeros and poles of the original zeta function, in order to bound the real parts of the zeros of the original zeta function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] By analogy, Kurokawa (1992) introduced multiple zeta functions whose zeros and poles correspond to sums of zeros and poles of the Riemann zeta function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] To make the series converge he restricted to sums of zeros or poles all with non-negative imaginary part.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p01] So far, the known bounds on the zeros and poles of the multiple zeta functions are not strong enough to give useful estimates for the zeros of the Riemann zeta function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] for *s* = 1/2 + *iT*, where the argument is defined by varying it continuously along the line with Im(*s*) = *T*, starting with argument 0 at ∞ + *iT*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] So the density of zeros with imaginary part near *T* is about log(*T*)/(2π), and the function *S* describes the small deviations from this.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The function *S*(*t*) jumps by 1 at each zero of the zeta function, and for *t* ≥ 8 it decreases monotonically between zeros with derivative close to −log *t*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] points where the function *S*(*t*) changes sign.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] This suggests that *S*(*T*)/(log log *T*)1/2 resembles a Gaussian random variable with mean 0 and variance 2π2 (Ghosh (1983) proved this fact).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] In particular |*S*(*T*)| is usually somewhere around (log log *T*)1/2, but occasionally much larger.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The exact order of growth of *S*(*T*) is not known.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] There has been no unconditional improvement to Riemann's original bound *S*(*T*) = *O*(log *T*), though the Riemann hypothesis implies the slightly smaller bound *S*(*T*) = *O*(log *T*/log log *T*).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The true order of magnitude may be somewhat less than this, as random functions with the same distribution as *S*(*T*) tend to have growth of order about log(*T*)1/2.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] In the other direction it cannot be too small: Selberg (1946) showed that *S*(*T*) ≠ *o*((log *T*)1/3/(log log *T*)7/3), and assuming the Riemann hypothesis Montgomery showed that *S*(*T*) ≠ *o*((log *T*)1/2/(log log *T*)1/2).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Numerical calculations confirm that *S* grows very slowly: |*S*(*T*)| < 1 for *T* < 280, |*S*(*T*)| < 2 for *T* < 6800000, and the largest value of |*S*(*T*)| found so far is not much larger than 3.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Riemann's estimate *S*(*T*) = *O*(log *T*) implies that the gaps between zeros are bounded, and Littlewood improved this slightly, showing that the gaps between their imaginary parts tend to 0.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Hadamard (1896) and de la Vallée-Poussin (1896) independently proved that no zeros could lie on the line Re(*s*) = 1.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Together with the functional equation and the fact that there are no zeros with real part greater than 1, this showed that all non-trivial zeros must lie in the interior of the critical strip 0 < Re(*s*) < 1.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] This was a key step in their first proofs of the prime number theorem.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Both the original proofs that the zeta function has no zeros with real part 1 are similar, and depend on showing that if *ζ*(1 + *it*) vanishes, then *ζ*(1 + 2*it*) is singular, which is not possible.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] for *σ* > 1, *t* real, and looking at the limit as *σ* → 1.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The most extensive computer search by Platt and Trudgian for counterexamples of the Riemann hypothesis has verified it for |*t*| ≤ 3.0001753328×1012.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Beyond that zero-free regions are known as inequalities concerning *σ* + *i t*, which can be zeroes.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The oldest version is from De la Vallée-Poussin (1899–1900), who proved there is a region without zeroes that satisfies 1 − *σ* ≥ ⁠*C*/log(*t*)⁠ for some positive constant *C*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] In other words, zeros cannot be too close to the line *σ* = 1: there is a zero-free region close to this line.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] This has been enlarged by several authors using methods such as Vinogradov's mean-value theorem.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The paper also presents an improvement to the second zero-free region, whose bounds are unknown on account of $|t|$ being merely assumed to be "sufficiently large" to fulfill the requirements of the paper's proof.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Hardy (1914) and Hardy & Littlewood (1921) showed there are infinitely many zeros on the critical line, by considering moments of certain functions related to the zeta function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Selberg (1942) proved that at least a (small) positive proportion of zeros lie on the line.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Levinson (1974) improved this to one-third of the zeros by relating the zeros of the zeta function to those of its derivative, and Conrey (1989) improved this further to two-fifths.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] In 2020, this estimate was extended to five-twelfths by Pratt, Robles, Zaharescu and Zeindler by considering extended mollifiers that can accommodate higher order derivatives of the zeta function and their associated Kloosterman sums.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Most zeros lie close to the critical line.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] More precisely, Bohr & Landau (1914) showed that for any positive *ε*, the number of zeros with real part at least 1/2+*ε* and imaginary part at between −*T* and *T* is $O(T)$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Combined with the facts that zeros on the critical strip are symmetric about the critical line and that the total number of zeros in the critical strip is $\Theta (T\log T)$ , almost all non-trivial zeros are within a distance *ε* of the critical line.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Ivić (1985) gives several more precise versions of this result, called *zero density estimates*, which bound the number of zeros in regions with imaginary part at most *T* and real part at least 1/2 + *ε*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] In 1914 Godfrey Harold Hardy proved that $\zeta \left({\tfrac {1}{2}}+it\right)$ has infinitely many real zeros.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Let $N(T)$ be the total number of real zeros, and $N_{0}(T)$ be the total number of zeros of odd order of the function $~\zeta \left({\tfrac {1}{2}}+it\right)~$ lying on the interval $(0,T]~$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Atle Selberg investigated the problem of Hardy–Littlewood *2* and proved that for any *ε* > 0 there exists such $T_{0}=T_{0}(\varepsilon )>0$ and *c* = *c*(*ε*) > 0, such that for $T\geq T_{0}$ and $H=T^{0.5+\varepsilon }$ the inequality $N(T+H)-N(T)\geq cH\log T$ is true.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Selberg conjectured that this could be tightened to $H=T^{0.5}$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The estimates of Selberg and Karatsuba can not be improved in respect of the order of growth as *T* → ∞.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Karatsuba (1992) proved that an analog of the Selberg conjecture holds for almost all intervals (*T*, *T*+*H*], $H=T^{\varepsilon }$ , where *ε* is an arbitrarily small fixed positive number.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The Karatsuba method permits to investigate zeros of the Riemann zeta function on "supershort" intervals of the critical line, that is, on the intervals (*T*, *T*+*H*], the length *H* of which grows slower than any, even arbitrarily small degree *T*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] This estimate is quite close to the one that follows from the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] has the same zeros as the zeta function in the critical strip, and is real on the critical line because of the functional equation, so one can prove the existence of zeros exactly on the real line between two points by checking numerically that the function has opposite signs at these points.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] where Hardy's Z function and the Riemann–Siegel theta function *θ* are uniquely defined by this and the condition that they are smooth real functions with *θ*(0) = 0.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] By finding many intervals where the function *Z* changes sign one can show that there are many zeros on the critical line.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] To verify the Riemann hypothesis up to a given imaginary part *T* of the zeros, one also has to check that there are no further zeros off the line in this region.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] This can be done by calculating the total number of zeros in the region using Turing's method and checking that it is the same as the number of zeros found on the line.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] This allows one to verify the Riemann hypothesis computationally up to any desired value of *T* (provided all the zeros of the zeta function in this region are simple and on the critical line).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] These calculations can also be used to estimate $\pi (x)$ for finite ranges of x .
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] where T is the largest known value such that the Riemann hypothesis is true for all zeros $\rho$ with $\Im {\left(\rho \right)}\in \left(0,T\right]$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Some calculations of zeros of the zeta function are listed below, where the "height" of a zero is the magnitude of its imaginary part, and the height of the *n*th zero is denoted by *γn*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] So far all zeros that have been checked are on the critical line and are simple.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] (A multiple zero would cause problems for the zero finding algorithms, which depend on finding sign changes between zeros.) For tables of the zeros, see Haselgrove & Miller (1960) or Odlyzko.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] A Gram point is a point on the critical line 1/2 + *it* where the zeta function is real and non-zero.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Using the expression for the zeta function on the critical line, *ζ*(1/2 + *it*) = *Z*(*t*)*e*−*iθ*(*t*), where Hardy's function, *Z*, is real for real *t*, and *θ* is the Riemann–Siegel theta function, we see that zeta is real when sin(*θ*(*t*)) = 0.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] This implies that *θ*(*t*) is an integer multiple of π, which allows for the location of Gram points to be calculated fairly easily by inverting the formula for *θ*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] They are usually numbered as *gn* for *n* = 0, 1, ..., where *gn* is the unique solution of *θ*(*t*) = *n*π.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Gram observed that there was often exactly one zero of the zeta function between any two consecutive Gram points; Hutchinson called this observation **Gram's law**.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] There are several other closely related statements that are also sometimes called Gram's law: for example, (−1)*n**Z*(*gn*) is usually positive, or *Z*(*t*) usually has opposite sign at consecutive Gram points.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The first failure of Gram's law occurs at the 127th zero and the Gram point *g*126, which are in the "wrong" order.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] A Gram point *t* is called good if the zeta function is positive at 1/2 + *it*.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The indices of the "bad" Gram points where *Z* has the "wrong" sign are 126, 134, 195, 211, ...
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] A *Gram block* is an interval bounded by two good Gram points such that all the Gram points between them are bad.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] For example, the interval bounded by *g*125 and *g*127 is a Gram block containing a unique bad Gram point *g*126, and contains the expected number 2 of zeros although neither of its two Gram intervals contains a unique zero.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Rosser et al. checked that there were no exceptions to Rosser's rule in the first 3 million zeros, although there are infinitely many exceptions to Rosser's rule over the entire zeta function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Gram's rule and Rosser's rule both say that in some sense zeros do not stray too far from their expected positions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The distance of a zero from its expected position is controlled by the function *S* defined above, which grows extremely slowly: its average value is of the order of (log log *T*)1/2, which only reaches 2 for T around 1024.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] This means that both rules hold most of the time for small *T* but eventually break down often.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Indeed, Trudgian (2011) showed that both Gram's law and Rosser's rule fail in a positive proportion of cases.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] To be specific, it is expected that in about 66% one zero is enclosed by two successive Gram points, but in 17% no zero and in 17% two zeros are in such a Gram-interval on the long run Hanga (2020).
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Assuming the Riemann hypothesis one can ask what further regularities might govern the distribution of the zeros of the zeta function on the critical line.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] One conjectural picture is that the critical zeros of the zeta function behave statistically like the eigenvalues of large random Hermitian matrices.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The idea began with Hugh Montgomery's work on the pair correlation conjecture for the zeros of the zeta function.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] After a suitable rescaling to account for the increasing density of zeros with height, the conjectured pair correlation function agrees with that of eigenvalues in the Gaussian unitary ensemble (GUE) in random matrix theory.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The connection was tested numerically by Andrew Odlyzko, who found that the spacing statistics of zeros high on the critical line agree closely with the predictions of GUE random matrix theory.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The agreement extends beyond nearest-neighbor spacings to higher correlation functions, and is widely regarded as strong evidence that the zeros are modeled by the same local statistics as random matrices.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The random matrix analogy is also related to the Hilbert–Pólya conjecture, and to ideas from quantum chaos.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] In quantum chaotic systems, eigenvalues often obey random matrix statistics, so the appearance of the same statistics in the zeros of the zeta function can be interpreted as evidence that they may arise from a selfadjoint operator or from a chaotic dynamical system.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] This gives a heuristic picture of why the zeros might lie on a spectral line and why their spacings exhibit strong repulsion rather than random clustering.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] For the Riemann zeta function, the relevant ensemble is that of the unitary group.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Random matrix theory has also led to conjectures about the growth of moments of the zeta function on the critical line.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] In particular, Jonathan Keating and Nina Snaith used averages over random unitary matrices to predict the main constants in asymptotic moment formulas such as ${\frac {1}{T}}\int _{0}^{T}|\zeta (1/2+it)|^{2k}\,dt$ as $T\to \infty$ .
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Their conjectures separate a universal random-matrix factor from an arithmetic Euler product factor, and have influenced later work on moments and ratios of L-functions.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Random matrix theory and quantum chaos are thus heuristic framework surrounding the Riemann hypothesis, even though no proof of the hypothesis is known from this approach.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Mathematical papers about the Riemann hypothesis tend to be cautiously noncommittal about its truth.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] Of authors who express an opinion, most of them, such as Riemann (1859) and Bombieri (2000), imply that they expect (or at least hope) that it is true.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The few authors who express serious doubt about it include Ivić (2008), who lists some reasons for skepticism, and Littlewood (1962), who flatly states that he believes it false, that there is no evidence for it and no imaginable reason it would be true.
[src:analytic-number-theory/riemann-hypothesis-p02] The consensus of the survey articles (Bombieri 2000, Conrey 2003, and Sarnak 2005) is that the evidence for it is strong but not overwhelming, so that while it is probably true there is reasonable doubt.
